< review>
I came here around 10:30sh weekday evening.

It is the first Cybercafe i visited here in US.

Cafe Attendant: The attendant is nice and approachable. He gladly assist me (even though arrived the cafe when he was playing his game).

Business Hour:
11am-2am (how i wish they are open till 4am)

Location: Located in Koreatown (Vermont and Olympic) in a Plaza. 2nd floor, well lit building and safe location.

Price: $4 per hour (with account) if you sign up for new account it would be $10 which includes 3 hours in the account.

Oh, they accept debit card for payment + .50cents transaction charge.

Toilet: If you are like me who needs to pee alot, the toilet is not located inside the cafe. The toilet is conveniently accessible outside the cafe near the elevator (ask the cafe attendant for the key)

Computer Units: I would say their computer units has a very good specs. it handled dota2 in ultra-high settings without any issue.

Internet is fast. No Lags. No Delays.
Computer peripherals is in good to perfect condition
Huge Monitor
Comfortable Seats.</review>

Few days ago, my front driver side begin to develop a tiny leak between the tire and the rim that would deflate my tire completely in two days. <review>This is not my regular gym, but there are some things that I love about Manteca that keep me going there as well. I've never had less than a good interaction with the staff at this In Shape. Last week I went in looking for a certain machine but unsure whether they had it. Amanda (who was at the desk when I checked in) called over a trainer and asked him to show me the location of the machine I was searching for. He took me to the first of several machines and asked what I was looking for. I was able to describe the exercise I was replacing in my workout and he took me directly to a machine that did exactly what I needed.

There are always towels, the locker room has always been clean, I LOVE that they have a separate changing room, and the fans in the treadmills are amazing. There are almost always enough free weights (though there could be more of the light weights outside of Group X) and kettlebells and I rarely have to wait for a machine.

I have been to Manteca less than 10 times but have had multiple positive engagements with Amanda, the manager. As I've been an In Shape member for nearly 18 months and seen my regular club's manager maybe 30 times, this stands out to me. (To be fair, I work out very early at my home club and later in the day when I make it to Manteca.)

Overall, I'm very impressed with this club.</review><user_id>101465184045564772056< /user_id>< gmap_id>

WeAreBrish< /user_name>
< text>
Very bad first experience.  Not always good to go through a middle company (which is what Fiesta is).  It was my first time getting car insurance, so I went through Fiesta Auto Insurance in Madera (which is lead by the same person who works in the Dinuba office).  I paid my first monthly payment and starting fee of $200.  Things went normal at first:  I got my next bill in the mail, went in and paid it off three days before the due date and also upgraded my insurance policy for a total of $138.  Two weeks later, my insurance was canceled because Fiesta never submitted my payment to Reliant General, the company through which they were giving me insurance.  My bill for my next payment never came in the mail... It took a while before I found out I was driving without insurance.

I went into Fiesta and the first worker put the blame completely on me.  He tried to send me on my way, but I refused.  I spoke to a second worker and started a new policy for $79.  He did give me $63 back because my last policy didn't work.  At this point, I still believed the last policy cancellation was my fault.  I then received a cancellation fee in the mail from Reliant General for $45 along with a warning for "collection proceedings".  I would later receive a verbal warning "We will send our collectors."

After some investigation, taking time and energy out of my days, I finally found out the fault was on Fiesta.  To this day, no one has admitted fault and apologized for it.

Over the next two months, I tried to get in contact with the manager/accountant, Andrea, (who actually works at an office in a different city, Dinuba), to fix my $45 cancellation fee.  In the last few weeks, I was playing a little game of phone tag with her, as she would never call me back.  Andrea finally did part of her job and contacted me.  She never admitted mistake or apologized, but when asked why my payment wasn't submitted, she simply stated, "I don't know why."  Also, she decided not to pay my $45 fee though she knew it was the mistake of her company.

Even after all the frustration and being cheated out of some money, I cannot break away from my current Fiesta policy as I have invested too much money already.

Extremely bad first experience.  At least I didn't get in a car wreck during those 2 1/2 weeks I was unknowingly uninsured.</text>

Fantastic ! Heard about this place on a local news station And it was worth it! It was super hot today so an Italian ice sounded perfect . The parking in the area is a bit tricky but not impossible. The line at 4pm was a good 45 mins and wrapped around to behind the barbershop . So just plan accordingly and bring a hat and water since you are in direct sun in the line . The product is great and the staff is very friendly and are moving quickly for a small place ! I loved the rocket swirl which has every flavor and the pineapple was my fav ! Worth a try !! <Pictures>None</Pictures><Rate>5< /Rate>< name>
Courtney Jevis< /name>
< Text>
I remember when they first opened, I was on Melrose and the nice lady at the front gave me a free sample. It was delicious.

Now, two years later, boy have they GROWN! Multiple trucks, multiple locations in one day, private parties... you name it.

In the hot dry summer of LA, happy ice is the perfectly refreshing, sweet but not too sweet, light dessert that is sure to brighten your day and cool off your body.

Color changing spoons too!

Pro tip: they are almost always at the vegan fair on Bakman in Noho on Sundays.

Suggestion: Can you guys get sour spray? A lot of Hawaiian ice trucks have it, it gives a nice sour kick to any icy desserts (;

Love it!</Text>

113364123401419431603<//UserId.>
< username>
Alyson Levy</username>
< Date>
1568849964426<//Date>
< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< Review>
Good vibes and good ice!

I actually got happy ice from their truck just now on Sepulveda in Van Nuys near Petco. I was about to walk away because it didn't have the toppings I pictured wanting. I also wasn't that excited about any of the flavors.  The salesgirl was so nice that I felt guilty and got a small... I was so wrong..first off, I got the rainbow flavor (all of them).

The texture was unlike (in a Better way) any shaved ice place I've ever had. It was almost the texture of ice cream!
The way the flavors were stripes-- all separated-- but you could eat an individual color and it was that flavor-- allowed me to taste each flavor and they were ALL good, even the lemon.  NO TOPPING NEEDED.
I could go on... but I'm afraid you won't read it and you must!
To all skeptics- just try it, you'll be more than pleasantly surprised. I'm not a natural reviewer--- but the whole package was such a good experience I was compelled to.

Awesome touch with the color changing spoon.< /Review>

<rating>3< /rating>< text>
If you like buying cheap products or products made in China that are also cheap or you want to support the Chinese economy then Walmart is the place you want to be.

Now to be fair they do have American made products in the store and from other countries, might have to search for it but they're there. And I cannot help the fact that my favorite French vanilla creamer is there in large quantities and is the cheapest in town.

Yes, I know people that work there so this is not about the people who work there. Still they're understaffed and it is difficult to find someone who can help you and if you do find someone who can help you it's most likely a trainee. For the staff please don't take this personally it's not about you the person, it is about management though. And there should be more floor managers out on the floor. The regular floor employees are always pulling double and triple duty to take care of everybody. For as poorly as this place maybe organized and run it is still 10 times better than some of the stores I have found back in the South near their main headquarters. Even after all the criticism I might have about shopping at Walmart you will find me in there from time to time looking for that cheap product. I would say good luck to you Walmart but from your profit rating I would say that you're already having the best luck in the world. Now if we can only get a Best Buy Store in Eureka. I have a local electronic scratch that I can't fix online. Maybe we can interest Best Buy with recent departure of Kmart store at the south end town. Or maybe at the soon to be old Sears store. I hear things aren't going well for them either.< /text>

< Text>
Third smallest Walmart in the USA. Ridiculously small produce section, but grocery and frozen aisles are sort of OK, they take up right side of store. You could do all of your grocery shopping here if you're not picky about certain brands missing. Clothes in the middle, pet food & cosmetics on the right, electronics and auto in the back. They managed to fit a mini version of every normal Walmart section into a tiny space, and didn't do a bad job at it. Definitely not worse than having no Walmart at all. Also recently installed self-checkouts, which is a plus!<//Text>

<rating>5<//rating>< Review>
This Walmart may be a little smaller than the average one but it gets the job done for the very most part! It's got a little bit of everything---with the exception of fresh produce and fresh meat/chicken/fish. For those you will need to go to Safeway (in Eureka). Or Ray's(to the South or north of Eureka).  Or to health food store or the "Canned Food Store". But really for most anything else-- this Walmart can be your friend. Friendly,helpful staff/crew and the best manager of any store I can remember ever meeting and dealing with. (James)  Good job, Walmart !</Review>

The workers have a cheery attitude but people who normally go in look to be under high levels of stress, just high or overloaded with children i'm noticing..i would suggest maybe our local walmart training their staff to not only have a friendly and professional attitude but maybe an event to be more involved in the community. i have observed poor attitude or inability to show empathy from both worker and customer alike but i think having the employees make a public event for families would be not only an excellent business opportunity but a great way to get happy customers and have happy workers. Just an idea from a local customer here who has both worked and been a customer. And, just one more thought, being that its summer and weather is changing around the world, keeping everyone cool, i think, should be a priority and a solution could be more air conditioning for workers and in the store, cooler filtered water at store drinking fountains for worker and customers. Maybe an hourly walk around the building with security guards (i would say 2 at a time due to the amount of people that are just hanging outside doing illegal activities and can be bothersome or rude to customers) offer a drink (of water) and ask them to go??? I only write a long review because these are the constant issues that make me not want to come back in my own community and these, to me, would make me want to come back. Honestly, our community also has a great college,both at CR and HSU that teach excellent skills to students who could certify as child care specialists and i think it would depreciate stress and increase shopping if walmart offered or funded proper child care for customers?? Just something that i believe many people would desire while getting household needed items. :)< /Text>< name>

< text>
This Walmart has NEW management!  NEW associates!  And NEW attitudes!

With the recent ouster of old management, some of which are facing criminal charges, this Walmart is undergoing much needed improvements.  New management has cleared out problem employees, hired 50+ new associates, and improved the overall customer experience.  New delivery schedules, new inventory procedures, and added employees mean shelves are better stocked, the store is cleaner, and customer service is improved.

Customers still need to consider that this Walmart is next to Eureka's largest homeless population camp behind the Bayshore Mall, and that some new store policies have been implemented to deter shoplifting, panhandling, and loitering by these local vagrants.  Overall, the store is 100% better than it was 3 months ago!

This Walmart, while small, does have a new produce section, offering a full array of fresh produce.  Due to store size, not all items that larger Walmarts carry, can possibly fit on their limited shelves, but they do have free Site to Store available online, so you can still get every item Walmart offers.

Go in and see the improvements!  While you are there, let the associates, and management, know that you notice the changes, make suggestions for improvements, and thank them for being there.  The employees are working hard to make this Walmart better for all customers and for themselves, let them know you appreciate their efforts!<//text>

<rate>3<//rate>< Text>
The ONLY Walmart in Humboldt County. Its in a very odd location, being part of the Bayshore Mall. Super small compared to any other Walmart I have ever seen. Prices are higher for most items here compared to WinCo 2 blocks away. Not enough parking. Getting in and out of the mall parking lot is a pain. NOT open 24/7. Not a Super Walmart. Puny selection compared to most other Walmarts. No appliances, bikes, automotive, bakery, take out food, small selection of electronics. Employees not really trained for their specific sections. Dont expect anyone in sporting goods to know anything about sporting goods or anyone in electronics to know how to set up a prepaid phone. If you need people who know what they are doing try Target instead.<//Text>

< Text>
This Walmart has NEW management!  NEW associates!  And NEW attitudes!

With the recent ouster of old management, some of which are facing criminal charges, this Walmart is undergoing much needed improvements.  New management has cleared out problem employees, hired 50+ new associates, and improved the overall customer experience.  New delivery schedules, new inventory procedures, and added employees mean shelves are better stocked, the store is cleaner, and customer service is improved.

Customers still need to consider that this Walmart is next to Eureka's largest homeless population camp behind the Bayshore Mall, and that some new store policies have been implemented to deter shoplifting, panhandling, and loitering by these local vagrants.  Overall, the store is 100% better than it was 3 months ago!

This Walmart, while small, does have a new produce section, offering a full array of fresh produce.  Due to store size, not all items that larger Walmarts carry, can possibly fit on their limited shelves, but they do have free Site to Store available online, so you can still get every item Walmart offers.

Go in and see the improvements!  While you are there, let the associates, and management, know that you notice the changes, make suggestions for improvements, and thank them for being there.  The employees are working hard to make this Walmart better for all customers and for themselves, let them know you appreciate their efforts!<//Text>

<userid>107794265061622558103</userid>< name>
Jasmine Westbrook< /name>
<Date>1482169571109<//Date><Rating>3</Rating>< Review>
It's unfortunate that they have to keep the shampoo, makeup, and some of the other beauty and health items under guard. It makes shopping for these items difficult and awkward, because the area they're in is very cramped and confusingly organized. It's so bad that I usually buy shampoo when I visit family -- 6 hours away -- rather than brave that cramped little corner of the store. You have to purchase those items before you leave the area.
They also are chronically understocked in other areas of the store, and the layout is confusing.
The employees have always been friendly and as helpful as possible, and it really isn't their fault that shoplifting necessitated the shampoo guard, or that the pot growers buy all of their storage tubs around harvest season, or that the delivery trucks come less frequently here than to stores in the rest of CA. I give the employees 5 stars for carrying on.</Review>
